med with three different approaches: (1) the subject and mouse were in one room and the control mouse was in a separate room; (2) the subject and both mice were in the same room; and (3) the mice were in the same room and the subject viewed them through a
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 one-way glass from a separate room.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  According to Dennis V. Waite, writing in the May 1975 issue of}{\i\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 Probe the Unknown,}{\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 the experimental mice required only 87 percent as much time to awaken as the control mice.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Researcher Adrian Parker used positive motiv\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
ation in experiments with gerbils. Following periods of mild food deprivation, the animals were given opportunities to press one of two keys, one of which provided food. The keys were randomly changed by a computer. The animal was \'93\loch\f0 
free to respond at its \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
wn pace, making choices whenever it felt so inclined. It may be that animals have flashes of precognition only intermittently, and this schedule allowed them to take full advantage of these,\'94\loch\f0  Parker stated.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  One of the advantages of the procedures used, a\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ccording to the researcher, was that when the gerbil did respond, the only information regarding the possible correctness of his response was at the next position on the paper tape which had not yet come into the tape reader and had no effect on the elect
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
onic logic. Waite also pointed out that people in the room with the animal could provide no clues because they had no way of knowing which key was the right one. They couldn't see the parts of the tape about to enter the machine's reader. The randomness o
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  the tapes was rechecked after runs.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 There was a significant problem: an overestimate of actual trials since within-trials (before the keys were reactivated) were also counted even though they never led to reward. There was also \hich\f0 
\lquote \loch\f0 some ambiguity\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  in the \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 number of responses since the gerbils tended to \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 attack\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
 the keys after they had missed the food for several times in a row.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Nevertheless,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Waite continued, \'93\loch\f0 the animals obtained significantly more than chance number of rewards (55 percent). Different a\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
nimals also scored in various levels of success."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0  In some ways the mystery of animal behavior is considerably less than it was several years ago. A leading animal behavior researcher, Nikko Tinbergen, has stated: \'93\loch\f0 If one applies the term (ESP) to percept
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ion by process not yet known to us, then extrasensory perception among living creatures may well occur widely. In fact, the echolocation of bats, the function of the lateral line in fishes and the way electric fishes find their prey are all based on proce
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 ses which we did not know about\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and which were thus \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 extrasensory\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  in this sense\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 
only 25 years ago."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Yet, there are many kinds of animal behavior which clearly meet the definition of extrasensory perception\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 that is, the animal will be aware of events, co\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
nditions, etc., that cannot be traced to our present knowledge of the five senses. At this point there is little reason to believe that extrasensory perception in animals is different than it is in humans. It would seem safe to assume that when we learn m
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
re about extrasensory perception and psi (a Greek letter used generically for all types of psychic phenomena) our knowledge can be applied to both animal and human subjects. If, for example, we discover that awareness of consciousness is not something tha
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 is a product of the mechanical-chemical function of the body and not something limited by the space-time structure of the body, then the explanation of ESP may not reside in the body-organic brain-nervous system, but on other levels. In this case the dif
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 erences\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 if they exist\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 between animal and human paranormal abilities cannot be found merely by studying the differences in physical systems.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  One area of study of extrasensory perception in animals has to do with psi trailing cases. Homing is a familiar ph\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
enomenon. A creature such as a homing pigeon is taken from its home in a closed container and then released many miles distant, and it will find its way back to its home. It is believed that homing involves cues from star and sun positions, geomagnetic fi
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ld gradients, and so on, which enable the animal to determine where it is in relation to its target. This phenomenon, however, does not explain how animals can find their way to an unknown target or to places they have never been.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 In psi trailing, the animal finds its way to a new place never visited before and of which it knows nothing. One of the most famous stories regarding this talent is about a young female collie, Bobbie. She was driving with her family from Ohio to their n
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
w home in Oregon, a place where Bobbie had never been. During a stop in Indiana, Bobbie wandered away and after an exhaustive search by the family they finally had to give up and continue on their journey.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Nearly three months later, a skinny and somewhat\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 battered Bobbie showed up on the doorstep of the new Oregon home. In addition to the collar, there were several identifying marks and scars. A man by the name of Charles Alexander read about Bobbie's journey in a newspaper and he determined to follow her
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
trail from Indiana to Oregon. Alexander placed ads in strategically located newspapers and found a number of people who claimed to have temporarily cared for a collie of Bobbie's description. When the trail was mapped out it was found that Bobbie picked a
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 very reasonable route with few detours.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  J. B. Rhine and Sara Feather have surveyed fifty-four psi-trailing cases from their files in the Parapsychology Laboratory. The cases were chosen because they met their criteria of providing a reliable source of in
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
formation; a specific characteristic, such as a nametag or identifiable scar; general sense and internal consistency of the case; and adequate supporting data, such as independent corroboration of testimony, availability of the animal for inspection, etc.
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
Four of the cases involved birds and the remainder were with dogs and cats. Twenty-five of the cases involved distances of more than thirty miles. While fifty-four cases may not be a large number, they lend considerable support to the presence at least in
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 some animals of psi-trailing ability.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Another area of investigation of unusual perception in animals has to do with apparitional cases and with haunted places. The stories are many of dogs howling upon the death of some person. The abilities of animals t
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
o be aware of ghosts, disincamate beings, etc., will be related in a later chapter, but we might mention here that psychic investigators have been known to take dogs, cats, or other animals along as they are believed to be more sensitive to subtle fields 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
han humans. Raymond Bayless and Ernesto Bozzano have written several books dealing with this matter, and Dr. Robert Morris, mentioned earlier, in an informal study reported that a friend took a dog, cat, rat, and rattlesnake to an allegedly haunted house 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 aving two \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 bad vibes\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  rooms in which murders had been committed. \'93\loch\f0 
When introduced to one of these rooms, the dog, cat, and snake reacted as though they were being threatened. The rat remained quite calm. None of the four animals reacted out of the ordinar\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 y\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 when introduced to one of the other rooms in the house which had no comparable past history. Of additional interest is that when humans entered the \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 bad vibes\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
 room, they reported a temperature drop, estimated by one to be about 20 degrees Fahrenheit; an\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 actual thermometer recorded no temperature drop at all,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 Dr. Morris relates in an article, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 Animals and ESP,\'94\loch\f0  written for the October 1973 issue of}{\i\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 Psychic.
\par }{\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  The Psychical Research Foundation has initiated studies using animals as responders in out-of-body\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 experience (OOBE) studies. Gerbils, dogs, hamsters, and cats have been used in these experiments. In preliminary studies it was found that a cat owned by a person who was being tested for OOBE became intensely quiet during the time it was being \'93
\loch\f0 \hich\f0 visited\'94\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
by its owner. It was found that the cat's quiet time coincided with that pinpointed by the OOBE'er as being the period he had visited his pet. More on these experiences later.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Some research has centered around the testing of animals that have displayed u\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
nusual degrees of higher intelligence. Occasionally in one country or another an animal will emerge that apparently can do rather complex arithmetic, spell out intelligent sentences, and do various kinds of ESP tricks. Most of these are dogs and horses wh
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ch have been taught to respond to gestures or verbal questioning. They usually perform by selecting by nose or mouth lettered or numbered blocks or by tapping out the answers or, in the case of dogs, by barking.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Perhaps the best-known horse to perform in\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 this manner was Clever Hans. The German horse baffled audiences and scientists alike until it was discovered that Hans couldn't perform unless someone was present who knew the correct answer. Hans was such a careful observer of those around him that he a
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
parently was cued by the head positions of observers. When he started tapping his answers, those present would lean forward to get a good view. Once the horse had tapped the correct number of times, those who knew the answer would involuntarily, relax and
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 lean back again and thus indicate to Hans when to stop. If these cues were not available to Hans, he would keep on tapping until tired or until cued by some other signal.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  But a number of other animal performers have not been so easy to figure out. Suppos\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
edly, Durov, a Russian animal trainer, for a number of years was able to demonstrate telepathy between himself and his animals to the satisfaction of scientists who investigated the phenomena. We will take a closer look at some of these highly unusual ani
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
als and their feats later, some of which demand a reassessment of our theories concerning animal intelligence. Missie, the clairvoyant terrier, presents us with a myriad of baffling questions, as does the intelligent interchange between Fred Kimball and B
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 atrice Lydecker and a host of four-legged conversants.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  The Elberfield horses are not easy to explain, and Lady, a horse owned by Mrs. Claudia Fonda, performed some remarkable ESP feats. The Rhines twice investigated the horse, and initially found the ani
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
mal capable of what appeared to be true ESP performance. Later, however, the scientists found the horse only able to produce when given access to cues. One of the most thoroughly researched animals was Chris the Wonder Dog. He was owned by George Wood and
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
was investigated during the late 1950s by Remi Cadoret at the Parapsychology Laboratory at Duke. Chris would respond to verbal questions by pawing the correct answers on Wood's forearm. Wood taught Chris to guess which of five standard ESP symbols were en
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 c\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
losed in opaque envelopes. He pawed once for circle, two for cross, and so on. Chris reportedly was able to run through a pack of twenty-five cards with a very high degree of accuracy even though no one else knew the order of the cards, thereby seemingly 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 uling out the possibility that the dog was receiving the messages telepathically.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Yet, when Cadoret endeavored to repeat the performance, an interesting thing happened\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Chris\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  score dipped way below chance. This often happens with human ESP subjects and i
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
s thought to be due to negative psychological factors. Some investigators have used this phenomenon to argue that animal ESP is similar or identical to human ESP, while others contend that animals such as Chris are being telepathically cued by their owner
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  who may not be aware of their own ESP abilities. In any case these animals would have to be responsive to telepathic messages.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  J. B. Rhine suggests three other categories of human-animal psi communications: a reaction to the distant distress or death of\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 the animal's owner; anticipation of a positive event such as the return home of the owner after a long absence; and a reaction to impending danger either to the animal itself or to the animal's owner.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  As an example of the above, Dr. Morris cites the cas\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
e of a dog being quartered by a veterinarian while the owners were some distance away vacationing in Florida. The dog started howling uncontrollably one morning at ten a.m. and continued for an hour. Examination revealed nothing wrong with the dog. When t
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 e owners were told of the incident, they explained that during that precise time they were stranded on top of their car during a flash flood. They were rescued at eleven a.m.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Investigators continue to ponder whether humans can influence the behavior of l\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 ower animals, in a sense \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 willing\'94\loch\f0 
 them to bark so many times, turn in one direction rather than another, etc. Studies have been carried out with everything from bats to butterfly larvae and sufficient evidence has been produced to indicate that something\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
is going on. But some have made a case for psychokinesis in humans, while others have contended that the results clearly reveal ESP in animals. More than likely, definitive answers will not emerge until we know more about psi in general. At the moment it 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
eems to be reasonable to assume that animal owners can have psychokinetic powers and that animals do have ESP abilities. For that matter, how do we know that animals are not willing us to turn in a desired direction or telepathically informing us that it 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 s time to eat?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0  In concluding his article. Dr. Morris stated: \'93\loch\f0 
The evidence from anecdote and experiment that ESP is present in other species besides our own is considerable. Results with animals are at least as positive and consistent as human results, p\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
robably much more so. The only conclusive refutation of elaborate counter-explanations involving experimenter psi, etc., is the development of a large body of interrelated facts about the exact processes involved. I think the beginnings of such may be at 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 and..."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Discussing the implications of psi research with animals, Dr. Morris explained, \'93\loch\f0 
The finding of considerable evidence for psi in animals already has one important implication. It tells us that psi is apparently not of recent evolution..."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 There are some other implications that can be drawn. The evidence on hand would seem to indicate that there is an awareness beyond the so-called normal senses. This awareness puts the subject not only in contact with his immediate environment but also wi
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
h things and events at some distance. This awareness may be shared by not only humans and animals but all living things. If this should happen to be the case, then life, regardless of the form it takes, would seem to be enveloped by a universal and unifyi
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
g consciousness. Each thing would be related to everything else, and each life form would to some minute degree be affecting and influencing everything in the universe. These possibilities and some ways of looking at psychic abilities will be explored in 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 he following chapter.
