\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 Beyond the edge of history, man built the pyramids on the Giza plain of Egypt. How far back no one really knows. They are the only surviving monoliths of a once great civilization long since reduced\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 to dust by the changing sands of the Sahara or perhaps swallowed by the waters of the Atlantic.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Did these mountains grow there by the Nile nourished for days and years by slaves forced to raise a tomb unto some vainglorious king, or were they the inspir\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ed creation of mental giants fired with the light of erecting on earth the very knowledge of the universe? Who? Why? How? When?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  The questions can be raised, but the answers are limited to conjecture. Whatever the answers they are not likely to be the rig\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ht ones. Peering back at man's attempts over the centuries to explain the riddles of his world, one realizes that every answer offered about the nature of something\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 what it is, how it works\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 
sooner or later is set aside by a new conclusion. This is the way\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
it has been and this is the way it is likely to be for some time to come. The human mind simply has not evolved to the point where it can totally comprehend anything. It is our lot to be content with trading fragments for bigger and better fragments. But 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 he game goes on and with it the dream of discovering more tomorrow.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Beside the pyramids stands the Sphinx, silent sentinel of the passing parades, the touch of an enigmatic smile playing along the corners of lips frozen less by stone than by silence. Par\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
t beast, part man, part god, symbolic perhaps of the soul on a journey ... an animal on the way to becoming a god? We ponder and find more joy in our poetry man our experiments, for man is also a mystic. Or perhaps he was a mystic before he was a man; soa
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 ing high in the heavens on eagle's wings or listening to the whispers of nature beside a mountain den, how close then to me reality of things?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  We are not always sure of the origin of our discoveries, whether they come to us from our long-forgotten past, \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
or are the product of the rational mind, or are inspirations from having for a moment touched the divine. Questions asked sooner or later bear fruit. The fruit may not last, but while it does it serves as nourishment for another step. Antoine Bovis had pa
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 u\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
sed beside the Sphinx before passing on to the Great Pyramid. He was still wondering about the strange combination of man and beast depicted in the huge statue when he entered the King's Chamber. Maybe it was this thought that made him notice a small dead
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 animal in one corner of the room. He was fascinated by the discovery that the creature\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 obviously long dead\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 
had not deteriorated but had simply mummified.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Something told Bovis that one of the secrets of this occurrence was the shape of me pyramid, that th\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
e shape altered the energy fields inside in such a manner that instead of rotting the animal dehydrated. He tested this hypothesis when he returned home to France. He built model pyramids, constructed to the scale of the Great Pyramid and also aligned on 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
he north-south axis. Dead animals placed inside the models at a location approximating that of the King's Chamber mummified without spoiling. The French experimenter had launched the new era of pyramid construction.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  His studies came to the attention of a\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 Czechoslovakian radio engineer named Kari Drbal. Interested in wave fields, crystals, and so on, Drbal wondered what influence pyramid space would have on metal structures, and he found that razor blades could be resharpened if placed inside model pyrami
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 d\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
s. His patented pyramid razor-blade sharpeners came to the attention of two American reporters on tour of the iron curtain countries in pursuit of new scientific discoveries. They mentioned the pyramid experiments in their book,}{
\i\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 Psychic Discoveries Behind t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 he Iron Curtain,}{\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 and started a craze for pyramidology in this and a number of other countries. Interest grew as investigators\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 from basement tinkerers to professional researchers\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 
found that unusual phenomena did, indeed, occur inside pyramids.
\par 
