\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  It would be a mistake to assume that all animals are pure and saintly. Many cases have been cited where animals have saved human life. We should not overlook, however, those instances when pets have turned 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
on their masters for reasons not at all clear. A relative of mine was nearly killed by a bull he had raised from a calf and treated like a pet. Only the intervention of his bulldog saved his life. Dogs, too, have been known to kill or seriously cripple th
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 se who have cared for them.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Vitus Droscher in}{\i\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 The Friendly Beast}{\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  describes another human failing\hich\f0 
\emdash \loch\f0 deceit\hich\f0 \emdash \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 shared by animals, in this instance a baby beaver. He belonged to a colony that was fed every morning. Always wanting the best dainties, he was always first at the feeding place.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0  \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 One day, however,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Droscher explains, \'93\loch\f0 it was late for feeding time, and w\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
hen it lumbered out of the water all the larger and adult beavers were already gathered around the trough. Thereupon the baby dived back into the river and slapped the water three times with its broad tail. In beaver language that is the alarm signal for 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 xtreme danger. Like a flash, all the other beavers vanished from sight in the water, and the cheeky little fellow had the feed trough to itself."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Pets will sometimes steal food from our tables. If we argue that they do not know any better, do we use the \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 same argument when they save our lives? Vincent and Margaret Gaddis tell the story in}{
\i\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 The Strange World of Animals and Pets}{\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  of a cat that repented of a bad deed and tried to make amends.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  It seems that Timothy was so trusted that the pet canary was allowed\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
 free flight of the house. But one day Timothy proceeded to eat the bird. He was punished for his crime and driven from the house in disgrace. But several hours later, he returned. \'93\loch\f0 
In his mouth he carried, unharmed, a nestling sparrow which he deposited \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t the feet of his mistress."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Our usual definitions of instinct clearly do not accurately describe the quality of love and devotion demonstrated so often by animals. If survival is so important to them, why do they risk death to save the lives of humans a
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 nd other animals? Curly, our half-coyote, half-shepherd, clearly understood that Skitter, our small terrier, faced being hit by a tractor. He raced in front of the machine and rolled her out of the way.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Dolphins will go to any length to save their kind a\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 nd are fearless in the face of danger. \'93\loch\f0 
When one of the largest and most dangerous predators in the world, a thirty-foot long killer whale, dashes in among a school of dolphins, who break into shrill whistles of alarm, it might be thought that the beasts \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 w
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 ould all flee in panic\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \hich\f0 as men often do in a similar situation,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  Droscher states. \'93\loch\f0 
But that is not what occurs. First the dolphins try to rescue injured companions; only then do they make off."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Among the many enigmas of dolphins is their kindly treatment \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 toward us regardless of how we treat them. Droscher comments that \'93\loch\f0 
men have all too consistently persecuted, captured, shot, and killed dolphins. Nevertheless, not a single case has ever been recorded of a dolphin's making a hostile gesture toward a man\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 o
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t even when the man is engaged in killing the dolphin."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  The Gaddises in their excellent writings on animals mention several instances where dogs have faced death to save another animal. One of their stories concerns a man named Eldon Bisbee who lived in \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
New York City and owned a small French poodle. One night a taxicab driver came to his door with his injured dog. He told Bisbee that he had been driving through a snowstorm when he stopped to keep from hitting a German shepherd. The dog refused to get out
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
of the way. When he shouted at the animal, it came to his window and whined and then ran to a snowbank. The cab driver got out of his car and discovered the injured poodle. The shepherd stood above her wagging his tail. After he picked up the small dog an
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 d\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  put her in his car he looked around for the shepherd, but he had gone.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Dr. W. F. Sturgill was a physician for the Norfolk and Western Railroad. He also owned several fine dogs and was president of the National Foxhunters Association. He treated a friend\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
's dog for an injury suffered on barbwire. Approximately a year later Dr. Sturgill heard a scratching on his door. He opened the door to discover his friend's dog, but with him was another dog with injured and bleeding paws. The doctor took care of the in
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 j\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 uries and the dogs trotted off together.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Another story told by the Gaddises is of a bighorn sheep who during the summer of 1962 came down from the high country to the town of Mt. Baldy, California. The ewe was very sick. She was found and nursed back to 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 health by a doctor. Once well, she returned to the mountains. But two months later she brought her ailing newborn lamb to the doctor's home. Unable to heal the lamb herself, she had come back to the man who could help.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Confronted with a growing body of k\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
nowledge that destroys old theories regarding the restrictive nature of instinct, that animals were unable to reason, and so on, we must rethink our concepts of animal nature. The old models will not suffice.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Will our new knowledge provide us with greate\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
r respect for other life forms than our own? Will we gain a new kind of reverence for all of life? If we do, in what ways will this affect our lives? Will our new awareness and sensitivity demand different sources of food protein than meat? Will the day o
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  the hunter soon end? Organizations have been formed to protect the seals, the wolves, coyotes, dolphins, whales, certain birds\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 will this movement grow?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  What does the possible extinction of a species mean to us? How might it affect our lives? Scientist J\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
acques Cousteau has stated that unless we quickly learn to take care of our oceans they will be dead in not too many years. Others have suggested that the demise of life in the seas is soon followed by death on land. Such possibilities are another reason 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 or gaining a greater understanding of animals. Oceanographer John Todd speaks of this need for knowledge. He is quoted by Michael Schofield in an article, \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
The Smelly Factor,\'94\loch\f0  written for}{\i\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 Smithsonian}{\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0  magazine, as saying: \'93\loch\f0 
The oceanographic community has beg\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
un to realize the urgency of acquiring knowledge of how marine animals communicate. This is no longer purely an academic or scientific matter. The languages of animals are the means whereby they organize their lives in relation to each other\hich\f0 
\emdash \loch\f0 just as we do\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 .\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 Their communication is crucial to their survival, but the language of fish and other marine creatures probably represent the weakest link in their life histories. Their signals can be jammed or disrupted by extremely low levels of pollutants, and this co
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 u\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ld have a catastrophic effect on their social behavior. What I am saying is that insidious levels of pollution can alter social behavior in such a way as to prevent there even being a next generation."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Karl-Erik Fichtelius and Sverre Sjolander call for a\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  change in man's attitudes toward the animal kingdom in their closing remarks in their book}{\i\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 Smarter Than Man}{\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0  ?: \'93\loch\f0 
Even people who understand the doctrine of evolution intellectually have a hard time feeling strongly enough that man is a part of the living ea\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
rth. Man needs something to shake him to his roots, to impress him deeply with the fact that he does not own the earth. This something, which might give man the humility he needs, could be a greater knowledge of the other large-brained animals."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 The suggestion that man does not own the earth presents us with a somewhat startling perspective. We have for some time believed that if a nation could take and hold a body of land, its citizens could claim ownership. Once having ownership we believed
\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 ou\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 side of certain restrictions affecting other landowners\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 
we could do anything we wished with the land. It was ours to plow, plant, burn, flood, or place buildings on. Only humans had anything to say about it. No other life form was consulted or given any t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 h
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ought. If animals were involved at all, it was either to work the land or to be a part of the product produced. Now we have to ask if man alone has the right to judge how the earth is to be used. Does my title to the land provide me with greater rights th
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
n the animals that live and depend on it? Is man's survival and pleasure the only question of consequence? Are these questions fanciful, or do they have some significance? Do animals have any rights?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Down through the ages not all human beings were recogn\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ized as having rights. Sovereignty has often been limited to royal heads, dictators, etc., who alone determined the extent of rights held by others. Control still remains in the hands of a few in most nations today. The right to vote remained the privileg
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 of adult males until recent years, and not too long ago the males had to be property owners and of a certain race. For centuries, women, slaves, and to some extent children were chattel or property to be disposed of according to the whims of the owner. T
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 is is largely the position that animals are in today. Will animal rights ever become an issue? Likely this will depend on what we learn about other creatures than ourselves, what their position
\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 along with ours\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 is in the universe. A little more than a cent\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 u\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
ry ago a slaveowner would have scoffed if asked if slaves had rights. Is the question regarding animals ridiculous? Will it always remain so?
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  In his book}{\i\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 Man and Dolphin,}{\lang0\langfe1042\langnp0\insrsid13595813 \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 Dr. Lilly wonders what will happen if the dolphin achieves a bilateral conversationa\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 \hich\f0 l level. He suggests that if this should happen, the dolphin will become an ethical, legal, and social problem. \'93\loch\f0 
\hich\f0 Then,\'94\loch\f0 \hich\f0  he states, \'93\loch\f0 they will have reached the threshold of humanity, as it were ... if they reach the conversational abilities of any normal h\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 u\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
man being, we are in for trouble. Some groups of humans will then step forward in defense of these animals\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
 lives and stop their use in experimentation: they will insist that we treat them as humans and that we give them medical and legal protection. If t\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
e means of their further education in humanity is available, there probably will be an explosive development of such education."
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  Some may ask why this concern for animals when so many humans are oppressed and starving. Any argument that this book has put\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
 forth for the respect, appreciation, and protection of animals does not intend in any sense to minimize human problems\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and they are many\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 
nor in any manner to distract our attention from high-priority concerns.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0  But if our considerations of animals were d\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
irected only to the welfare of mankind alone, the priority would be reasonably high. This reason is not from the standpoint of balances in nature, nor from the roles animals play in our food production. The issue is greater than these: Our treatment of an
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 
mals is important to our own internal states. If we are to expand our horizons, to grow, to understand what the new physics means by the relatedness of each and every living thing, then our love and appreciation of all life is essential. In a world where 
\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af12\loch\f0 eelings and thoughts are things, our respect and reverence for all living things will be reflected in our own being.
